{{Internet}}
'''World Day Against Cyber Censorship''' is an online event held each year on March 12 to rally support for a single, unrestricted Internet that is accessible to all and to draw attention to the ways that governments around the world are deterring and censoring free speech online.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2011/03/march-12-world-day-against-cyber-censorship/72400/ |title=March 12: 'World Day Against Cyber-Censorship' |work=The Atlantic |date=12 March 2011 |accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref> The day was first observed on 12 March 2008 at the request of [[Reporters Without Borders]] and [[Amnesty International]]. A letter written by Jean-François Julliard, Secretary-General of Reporters Without Borders, and [[Larry Cox (Amnesty International)|Larry Cox]], Executive Director of Amnesty International, was sent to the Chief Executive Officers of Google, Yahoo!, Inc., and Microsoft Corporation to request observation of the day.<ref>[http://www.rsf.org/IMG/pdf/RWB-AI_.pdf Copy of a letter] dated 6 March 2009 from Jean-Francois Julliard, Secretary-General of Reporters Without Borders, and Larry Cox, Executive Director of Amnesty International, to Eric Schmidt, Chief Executive Officer, Google, Carol Bartz, Chief Executive Officer, Yahoo!, Inc., and Steve Ballmer, Chief Executive Officer, Microsoft Corporation.</ref> The annual event is symbolized by a logo created by [[Reporters Without Borders]] consisting of a computer mouse breaking free from a chain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.rsf.org/world-day-against-cyber-censorship-12-03-2010,36566 |title=World Day Against Cyber Censorship |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref>
==Netizen Prize== [[File:Tunisia24.jpg|thumb|RWB 2011 Netizen Prize]]
On World Day Against Cyber Censorship, Reporters Without Borders awards an annual ''Netizen Prize'' that recognizes an Internet user, [[blog]]ger, [[cyber-dissident]], or group who has made a notable contribution to the defense of online [[freedom of expression]].<ref>[https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2012/03/march-12-world-day-against-cyber-censorship "March 12: World Day Against Cyber-Censorship"], Maira Sutton, Electronic Frontier Foundation, 12 March 2012.</ref><ref name=RSFBrochure-April2012>[http://en.rsf.org/IMG/pdf/plaquette_uk_bd.pdf "Reporters Without Borders : For Freedom of Information"], Brochure, Reporters Without Borders, 16 April 2012.</ref> Starting in 2010 the prize has been awarded to:
* 2010: Iranian [[Women's rights in Iran|women's rights]] activists of the [[Change for Equality]] website, www.we-change.org.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.rsf.org/iranian-women-s-rights-activists-12-03-2010,36718 |title=Iranian women's rights activists win first Reporters Without Borders netizen prize with support from Google |publisher=Reporters Without Borders |date=13 March 2010 |accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref> * 2011: the founders of a Tunisian blogging group named Nawaat.org.<ref>{{cite web|author=Reporters Without Borders |url=http://en.rsf.org/netizen-prize-2011-14-03-2011,39791.html |title=Netizen Prize 2011 |publisher=Reporters Without Borders |date=25 March 2011 |accessdate=11 March 2013}}</ref> * 2012: Syrian [[Citizen journalism|citizen journalists]] and activists of the Media center of the Local Coordination Committees.<ref>[http://en.rsf.org/syrie-syrian-citizen-journalists-and-12-03-2012,42093.html "Syrian citizen journalists and activists capture 2012 Netizen Prize"], Reporters Without Borders, 13 March 2012.</ref> * 2013: Vietnamese blogger Huynh Ngoc Chenh.<ref>[http://en.rsf.org/reporters-without-borders-awards-07-03-2013,44178.html "Reporters Without Borders Awards Vietnamese blogger Huynh Ngoc Chenh"], Reporters Without Borders, 7 March 2013.</ref> * 2014: Saudi Arabian blogger [[Raif Badawi]].<ref name=RSFPrize2014>[http://en.rsf.org/maghreb-et-moyen-orient-reporters-without-borders-tv5monde-05-11-2014,47204.html "Reporters Without Borders - TV5Monde Prize for Press Freedom"], Reporters Without Borders, 5 November 2014</ref>
==Enemies of the Internet list==
In conjunction with World Day Against Cyber Censorship, Reporters Without Borders updates its ''Enemies of the Internet'' and ''Countries Under Surveillance'' lists.<ref>[http://www.france24.com/en/2014-03-13-reporters-without-borders-ennemies-internet-list/ "Reporters Without Borders releases 'Enemies of the Internet' list"], France24 (France Médias Monde), 13 March 2014.</ref><ref name=RSFWDACC-2008>{{cite web|url=http://en.rsf.org/first-online-free-expression-day-12-03-2008,26086 |title=First Online Free Expression Day launched on Reporters Without Borders website |publisher=Reports Without Borders |date=12 March 2008 |accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref>
